ce:section.ce:para:
To obtain the maximum emission intensity of SD-CDs, various ratios of SAA:DPC (1:1 (0.10:0.10 gm), 1:3 (0.05:0.15 gm) and 3:1 (0.15:0.05 gm) in 10 mL of EtOH and H2O (1:1, v/v) were heated in microwave and studied their emission spectral characteristics (Fig. S1 of Supporting Information). The fluorescence emission intensity of SD-CDs was maximum using 3:1 ratio of SAA:DPC, revealing 3:1 ratio of SAA and DPC was optimum concentration for the synthesis of SD-CDs via microwave method. The fluorescence emission peak of SD-CDs was gradually increased with increasing λEx from 310 to 320 nm, which is shown in Fig. S1b of Supporting Information. It can be clearly noticed that when λEx was 319 nm, the emission intensity of SD-CDs reached maximum, and then the emission intensity decreased with the change in excitation wavelength. Thus, λEx of 319 nm was selected as an optimum excitation wavelength for further investigations. The as-prepared SD-CDs displayed an intense λmax at 335 nm in the UV region, which is due to π–π* transition (CC conjugated bonds) and n-π* transition (CO bond) in SD-CDs. Furthermore, the fluorescence emission spectra of SD-CDs displayed a maximum λEm at 392 nm when applied λEx at 319 nm (Fig. 1
                        ). The inset photograph image showed that the solution of SD-CDs presented almost transparent with yellow color in daylight whereas bright blue emission exhibited under UV irradiation at 365 nm. In order to confirm the use of both SAA and DPC as precursors, the CDs are prepared individually using SAA and DPC as precursors. It can be clearly observed that the as-synthesized SD-CDs exhibited characteristic absorption peak at 335 nm whereas the CDs prepared from SAA and DPC showed different λmax as compared to λmax of SD-CDs (Fig. S2a of Supporting Information). Besides, the fluorescence emission spectra of CDs prepared from SAA and DPC as precursors are shown in Fig. 2
                        b of Supporting Information. The CDs prepared from SAA + DPC as a precursor showed the best emission spectra whereas CDs obtained from SAA and DPC as precursors displayed different emission spectra with low intensities. These data illustrated that the use of both SAA and DPC greatly improved the fluorescence and absorption spectral characteristics of CDs. In order to investigate the stability of SD-CDs, the fluorescence spectra of SD-CDs were investigated at different time intervals and shown in Fig. S3 of Supporting Information. As can be seen that the fluorescence spectra of SD-CDs are almost same intensity up to 10 days after that there is a slightly decrease in the intensity and ∼ 44 % fluorescence quenching is noticed at 90 days. This data suggests that the as-prepared SD-CDs are good stability which favors them to utilize as a notable fluorescent sensor in analytical sciences.
